WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
Hello, everyone.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:08.600
My name is Vedavyash.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:13.840
I work for a company that has a lot of shiny developers across the globe.

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:17.940
In one of those markers in the southern part of India, you'll find me sitting in front

00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:23.180
of my computer, building some shiny apps and programming with R, while occasionally interviewing

00:00:23.180 --> 00:00:26.360
people to join our team.

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:32.360
Last year, over 1,200 applicants applied for the R Shiny Developer role at Epsilon,

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.200
and we hired over 30 shiny developers that year.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.439
The volume of these candidates has helped us understand what to look for in a shiny

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:44.740
developer, and I'll be sharing some tips on how you can become a better shiny developer.

00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:49.380
You might call yourself a data scientist, analyst, biostatistician, or any of the hundreds

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:54.320
of titles that use R and Shiny, but as soon as you've built your first shiny app, you're

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:55.799
a software developer.

00:00:55.799 --> 00:01:00.320
We've noticed that many of the applicants would greatly benefit from following some

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:02.799
good software development practices.

00:01:02.799 --> 00:01:11.839
For example, can you tell what will be the output of this?

00:01:11.839 --> 00:01:15.120
If well-written, you can easily do that.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:18.839
How about now?

00:01:18.839 --> 00:01:23.519
It produces the same output as before, even the functions do the same thing as before.

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:29.760
But I hope it explains one of the many ideas about writing code that is maintainable.

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:33.160
But all the other ideas are just as simple as this one.

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:37.879
It's many small things like these that make up a good developer.

00:01:37.879 --> 00:01:42.000
Let's imagine that you're working in one of our shiny apps from our gallery called Future

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:43.599
Forests.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:48.519
This app allows you to visualize the future forest distributions of 12 species under four

00:01:48.519 --> 00:01:50.800
scenarios.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:54.959
The data source for this app is just a bunch of RDS files with some cryptic names, but

00:01:54.959 --> 00:01:58.639
the names are not that cryptic once you know what they represent.

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:03.559
The prefix of the file name corresponds to a scientific name, while the suffix of the

00:02:03.559 --> 00:02:07.400
file name corresponds to one of those scenarios.

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:10.679
Let's say you accidentally delete one of these files.

00:02:10.679 --> 00:02:14.919
Now you should get an error for a very specific selection in the app, while the rest of the

00:02:14.919 --> 00:02:16.759
app works just fine.

00:02:16.759 --> 00:02:22.880
So you don't realize that you have an error until someone complains about it.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.000
But now imagine that you have an R script where you check for the existence of a data

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.919
file for every combination supported by the app.

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:35.080
It should give you an error when some file is missing.

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:37.440
This is what we call a unit test.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:42.320
And trust me, this will save you from an embarrassment of disconnected from server.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:44.800
I know we've all been there.

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:50.160
You can easily write tests like these using test that and Shiny test two.

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:54.679
If you check out the function references for Shiny, you'll find over 250 functions listed

00:02:54.679 --> 00:02:55.679
over there.

00:02:55.679 --> 00:02:59.559
This can be overwhelming if you're just getting started with Shiny.

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:05.199
But I would highly recommend to go through the functions related to reactive programming.

00:03:05.199 --> 00:03:10.119
Reactive programming is the core concept of Shiny that differentiated from other frameworks.

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:14.880
Again, this seems like a lot of functions, but not really, because the input, output

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:17.520
and render functions all behave the same.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:23.479
Again, these functions can be grouped into one of these three shapes based on where they

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:29.039
are used in the logic, source, conductor or endpoint.

00:03:29.039 --> 00:03:32.759
You just need to remember three rules while working with these reactive functions.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:36.500
The shape determines how they can connect with each other.

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:39.940
You can connect as many reactive components as you want.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.539
Finally, you can also have many to many connections with them.

00:03:43.539 --> 00:03:48.059
The simpler you make the reactive connections, the easier it would be for a human to interpret

00:03:48.059 --> 00:03:52.380
it and for Shiny to perform fewer computations to get things done.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:59.740
Finally, I recommend going through the software engineering key skills that we internally

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:03.460
created to improve the...

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:05.020
Sorry.

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:12.100
Finally, I want to highlight a valuable resource that we consider greatly contribute to our

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:15.779
team's technical growth, the software engineering key skill sheet.

00:04:15.779 --> 00:04:21.459
We've put a lot of effort in building this, and we maintain it regularly.

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:26.279
This has been instrumental in guiding hundreds of Shiny developers towards their professional

00:04:26.279 --> 00:04:27.540
development goals.

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:33.220
And I hope this will help you find topics and resources as well.

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:37.140
Thank you so much for your attention, and you can find me in the Appsalon booth if you

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:38.019
have any questions.

